      ".eval) G ->\n      cl ≈ (dedup cr) := sorry\n```\n\nThis is the theorem we need to prove. The conditions are:\n1. `G` is a list of entries such that `cr` is well-defined on `G`.\n2. Each entry in `G` satisfies the property that the left side equals the evaluation of the right side of the entry (with `Exp.c` extracting the function part).\n3. `cl` is well-defined on `G`.\n\nThe conclusion is that `cl` is equivalent to `dedup cr`.\n\nTo prove this, I need to show that `cl` and `dedup cr` compute the same values on inputs from `G`.\n\nThe key insight is that both `cl` and `dedup cr` are defined in a way that depends on the list `G`. The `dedup` function specifically uses `G` to track which expressions have already been evaluated.\n\nLet's think about how to write the proof.\n\nFirst, I need to understand what the `≈` symbol means in this context. In Lean, especially with circuits, this often means that the two circuits compute the same result on all valid inputs.\n\nSo, I need to show that for any input `x` in the domain defined by `G`, `cl x` and `dedup cr x` produce the same output.\n\nThe proof will proceed by induction on the structure of the circuits `cl` and `cr`. Since both are defined recursively, I need to consider each constructor.\n\nLet's start the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Clap.Circuit\nimport Clap.Simulation\nimport Clap.Id\n\nnamespace Clap\n\n/-\n  This file introduces an optimization to remove duplicate checks.\n  The current version eliminates any `eq0` with an expression that has\n  already been met before. The same optimization should be applicable\n  to boolean checks, limb checks and other lookup arguments with minor\n  modifications.\n\n  Dedup is extremely valuable as it allows to write composable\n  circuits with many redundant checks without having to pay the price\n  in term of constraints.\n-/\n\nnamespace Dedup\n\nvariable {p : ℕ} [Fact (Nat.Prime p)]\n```\n\nNow I define the helper functions `to_nat` and `to_var` as specified.\n\n```tactics\ndef to_nat {F var : Type} (e : Exp F (ℕ × var)) : Exp F ℕ :=\n  match e with\n  | .v (v, _) => .v v\n  | .c f => .c f\n  | .add l r => to_nat l + to_nat r\n  | .mul l r => to_nat l * to_nat r\n  | .sub l r => to_nat l - to_nat r\n\ndef to_var {F var : Type} (e : Exp F (ℕ × var)) : Exp F var :=\n  match e with\n  | .v (_, v) => .v v\n  | .c f => .c f\n  | .add l r => to_var l + to_var r\n  | .mul l r => to_mul l r\n  | .sub l r => to_sub l r\n```\n\nNext, I define the boolean equality function `beq`.\n\n```tactics\ndef beq : (e1 e2 : Exp (ZMod p) Nat) -> Bool\n  | .v n1, .v n2\n  | .c n1, .c n2 => n1 = n2\n  | .add ll lr, .add rl rr => beq ll rl ∧ beq lr rr\n  | .mul ll lr, .mul rl rr => beq ll rl ∧ beq lr rr\n  | .sub ll lr, .sub rl rr => beq ll rl ∧ beq lr rr\n  | _,_ => false\n```\n\nNow, I define the core `dedup_` function with the specified behavior.\n\n```tactics\ndef dedup_ {var} (c : Circuit p (ℕ × var)) (n : ℕ) (set : List (Exp (ZMod p) ℕ)) : Circuit p var :=\n  match c with\n  | .nil => .nil\n  | .eq0 e c =>\n    if (to_nat e) ∈ set\n    then dedup_ c n set\n    else .eq0 (to_var e) (dedup_ c n ((to_nat e)::set))\n  | .lam k => .lam (fun x => dedup_ (k (n,x)) (n+1) set)\n  | .share e k => .share (to_var e) (fun x => dedup_ (k (n,x)) (n+1) set)\n  | .is_zero e k => .is_zero (to_var e) (fun x => dedup_ (k (n,x)) (n+1) set)\n  | .assert_range w e c => .assert_range w (to_var e) (dedup_ c n ((to_nat e)::set))\n```\n\nNext, I define the main `dedup` function as specified.\n\n```tactics\ndef dedup {var} (c : Circuit p (Nat × var)) : Circuit p var := dedup_ c 0 []\n```\n\nNow, I define `dedup'` as specified.\n\n```tactics\ndef dedup' (c : Circuit' p) : Circuit' p := fun var => dedup (c (Nat × var))\n```\n\nNext, I define the `Test` namespace with the example circuits.\n\n```tactics\nnamespace Test\n\nabbrev F7 := Clap.F7.F\n\ndef a        : Circuit' 7 := fun _ => .lam (fun x => .eq0 (.v x + .c 1) (.eq0 (.v x + .c 2) (.eq0 (.v x + .c 1) .nil )))\ndef expected : Circuit' 7 := fun _ => .lam (fun x => .eq0 (.v x + .c 1) (.eq0 (.v x + .c 2) .nil ))\n\n#guard s!\"{dedup' a Nat}\" = s!\"{expected Nat}\"\n\nend Test\n```\n\nFinally, I state the theorem `dedup_sem_pre` and provide a proof.\n\n```tactics\ntheorem dedup_sem_pre : ∀ (cl : Circuit p (ZMod p)) (cr : Circuit p (ℕ × ZMod p)) G,\n  wf G cl cr ->\n    List.Forall (fun entry => entry.l = (Exp.c entry.r.2).eval) G ->\n      cl ≈ (dedup cr) := by\n```\n\nNow, I need to prove this theorem. Let's think about how to approach this proof.\n\nThe key insight is that both `cl` and `dedup cr` are defined recursively, and their behavior depends on the list `G`. The `dedup` function uses `G` to track which expressions have already been evaluated.\n\nTo prove the equivalence, I need to show that for any input `x` in the domain defined by `G`, `cl x` and `dedup cr x` produce the same output.\n\nThe proof will proceed by induction on the structure of the circuits `cl` and `cr`. Since both are defined recursively, I need to consider each constructor.\n\nLet's continue with the proof:\n\n```tactics\n  intro cl cr G h1 h2\n  have h3 : ∀ (x : ℕ × ZMod p), G ∈ (cr x).domain := by\n    intro x\n    simp_all [Circuit.mem_domain]\n```\n\nWait, this doesn't look right. The hypothesis `h1` states that `G` is a list of entries such that `cr` is well-defined on `G`. This means that for each entry in `G`, the input to `cr` is valid.\n\nLet me reconsider. The `wf` hypothesis ensures that `G` is a valid list of entries for the given circuits. The `List.Forall` hypothesis ensures that each entry satisfies the specified property.\n\nThe key is that both `cl` and `cr` are defined in a way that depends on `G`. The `dedup` function specifically uses `G` to track which expressions have already been evaluated.\n\nTo prove the equivalence, I need to show that for any input `x` in the domain of `G`, `cl x` and `dedup cr x` produce the same output.\n\nLet's think about how to write this proof formally:\